        <section>
            <section.front>
                <doc.title toc-guid="I94cbc925e1e311da9c26e67ca3b71335">
                    <head parent="doc.title">
                        <bop/>
                        <bos/>
                        <label.name>§</label.name>
                        <label.designator>2:3.</label.designator>
                        <headtext>Legislative history of the statute</headtext>
                        <eos/>
                        <eop/>
                    </head>
                </doc.title>
            </section.front>
            <section.body>
                <para>
                    <bop/>
                    <bos/>
                    <paratext>The legislative history of the statute creating the Panel sheds light on its purposes.[
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>
                        <footnote.reference refid="I01d571c0680911e88f4a9c1f64101294">1</footnote.reference>] The Panel
                        has resorted to the legislative history of <cite.query w-src-number="0304913945"
                                                                               w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="LQ"
                                                                               w-normalized-cite="28USCAS1407"
                                                                               w-pub-number="1000546"
                                                                               ID="I08ce3940680811e8865b9f61650dcdcd">28
                            U.S.C.A. § 1407
                        </cite.query> on many occasions in construing the statute&apos;s provisions.[
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>
                        <footnote.reference refid="I01d598d0680911e88f4a9c1f64101294">2</footnote.reference>] The House
                        Judiciary Committee reported the following on the bill which was enacted to become <cite.query
                                w-src-number="0304913945" w-seq-number="00005" w-ref-type="LQ"
                                w-normalized-cite="28USCAS1407" w-pub-number="1000546"
                                ID="I08ced580680811e8865b9f61650dcdcd">28 U.S.C.A. section 1407</cite.query>:<?pagebreak label="11"?>
                    </paratext>
                    <display.quote>
                        <para>
                            <paratext><begin.quote ID="QT_0001"/>The objective of the legislation is to provide
                                centralized management under court supervision of pretrial proceedings of’ multidistrict
                                litigation to assure the “just and efficient conduct” of such actions.
                                <eos/>
                                <bos/>The committee believes that the possibility for conflict and duplication in
                                discovery and other pretrial procedures in related cases can be avoided or minimized by
                                such centralized management.
                                <eos/>
                                <bos/>To accomplish this objective the bill provides for the transfer of venue for the
                                limited purpose of, conducting coordinated pretrial proceedings.
                                <eos/>
                                <bos/>
                                <end.quote refid="QT_0001"/>[<footnote.reference
                                        refid="I01d598d1680911e88f4a9c1f64101294">3</footnote.reference>]
                            </paratext>
                        </para>
                    </display.quote>
                    <eos/>
                    <eop/>
                </para>
                <para>
                    <bop/>
                    <bos/>
                    <paratext>The legislative history clearly demonstrates that Congress intended the statute to commit
                        the decisions regarding the optimal handling of complex and multidistrict litigation to the
                        Judiciary.
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>The House Committee stated:
                    </paratext>
                    <display.quote>
                        <para>
                            <paratext><begin.quote ID="QT_0002"/>[A] number of factors should be weighed in the
                                selection of a transferee district; the state of its docket, the availability of
                                counsel, sufficient courtroom facilities, etc.
                                <eos/>
                                <bos/>These factors do not lend themselves to precise measurement.
                                <eos/>
                                <bos/>Consequently, the committee believes that the informed discretion of the judiciary
                                is the best method for resolving questions as to when and where cases should be
                                transferred for pretrial.
                                <eos/>
                                <bos/>
                                <end.quote refid="QT_0002"/>[<footnote.reference
                                        refid="I01d5bfe0680911e88f4a9c1f64101294">4</footnote.reference>]
                            </paratext>
                        </para>
                    </display.quote>
                    <eos/>
                    <eop/>
                </para>
                <para>
                    <bop/>
                    <bos/>
                    <paratext>Congress also recognized that transfer would not routinely be ordered in cases involving
                        few common issues of fact or in situations where there are few related cases.
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>This policy has been carried forward by the Panel in its transfer decisions.[
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>
                        <footnote.reference refid="I01d5bfe1680911e88f4a9c1f64101294">5</footnote.reference>] The House
                        Committee report states:
                    </paratext>
                    <display.quote>
                        <para>
                            <paratext><begin.quote ID="QT_0003"/>If only one question of fact is common to two or three
                                cases pending in different districts there probably will be no order of transfer, since
                                it is doubtful that transfer would enhance the convenience of’ parties and witnesses, or
                                promote judicial efficiency.
                                <eos/>
                                <bos/>It is possible, however, that a few exceptional cases may share unusually complex
                                questions of fact, or that many complex cases may share a few questions of fact.
                                <eos/>
                                <bos/>In either of these instances substantial benefit may accrue to courts and
                                litigants through consolidated or coordinated pretrial proceedings.
                                <eos/>
                                <bos/>
                                <end.quote refid="QT_0003"/>[<footnote.reference
                                        refid="I01d5e6f1680911e88f4a9c1f64101294">6</footnote.reference>]
                            </paratext>
                        </para>
                    </display.quote>
                    <paratext>This recognition of the variety of situations in which transfer questions might arise
                        resulted in the establishment of standards, but flexible standards, to govern transfer.
                        <eos/>
                    </paratext>
                    <eop/>
                </para>
                <para>
                    <bop/>
                    <bos/>
                    <paratext>The legislative history of the statute makes it clear that Congress intended transfer to
                        apply to the entire action for all pretrial proceedings.
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>Congress considered, and apparently rejected, a statute allowing transfer of only certain
                        claims or transfer for only limited purposes.
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>In hearings before the Senate Subcommittee on Improvements in Judicial Machinery on
                        October 20 &amp; 21, 1966, the following testimony was offered: <?pagebreak label="12"?>
                    </paratext>
                    <display.quote>
                        <para>
                            <paratext>
                                <ital><begin.quote ID="QT_0004"/>Mr. Tydings
                                </ital>
                                .
                                <eos/>
                                <bos/>The bill provides for the transfer of claims for pre-trial procedures.
                                <eos/>
                                <bos/>It has been suggested that this conceivably is too broad and that the transfer
                                should be for discovery under the Federal Rules of Civil Procedure only, leaving other
                                pre-trial matters to the transferor district, to be conducted at perhaps the same time
                                or later.
                                <eos/>
                                <bos/>
                                <end.quote refid="QT_0004"/>
                            </paratext>
                        </para>
                        <para>
                            <paratext><begin.quote ID="QT_0005"/>The suggestion is also that the “unit” which is
                                transferred under the bill, the claim, is too broad, and that only “issues of fact” need
                                be transferred.
                                <eos/>
                                <bos/>Do you have any thoughts with respect to those two points?
                                <eos/>
                                <bos/>
                                <end.quote refid="QT_0005"/>
                            </paratext>
                        </para>
                        <para>
                            <paratext>
                                <ital><begin.quote ID="QT_0006"/>Dean Neal.
                                    <eos/>
                                    <bos/>
                                </ital>
                                Let me take the second question first.
                                <eos/>
                                <bos/>I think the appropriate unit to deal with is a claim or a cross-claim or
                                counterclaim, because that is the basic unit under the Federal Rules of Civil Procedure
                                insofar as they deal with separability of actions.
                                <eos/>
                                <bos/>
                                <end.quote refid="QT_0006"/>
                            </paratext>
                        </para>
                        <para>
                            <paratext><begin.quote ID="QT_0007"/>Reference might be made specifically to <cite.query
                                    w-src-number="0304913945" w-seq-number="00010" w-ref-type="LQ"
                                    w-normalized-cite="USFRCPR42" w-pub-number="1000600"
                                    ID="I08df9e60680811e8865b9f61650dcdcd">Rule 42(b) of the Federal Rules of Civil
                                Procedure</cite.query>, which deals with the problem of consolidation.
                                <eos/>
                                <bos/>I might say that Senate Bill 3815 really provides for a procedure that. is quite
                                analogous to what <cite.query w-src-number="0304913945" w-seq-number="00011"
                                                              w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="USFRCPR42"
                                                              w-pub-number="1000600"
                                                              ID="I08df9e61680811e8865b9f61650dcdcd">Rule 42
                                </cite.query> provides for, where cases are pending in the same district, and <cite.query
                                        w-src-number="0304913945" w-seq-number="00012" w-ref-type="LQ"
                                        w-normalized-cite="USFRCPR42" w-pub-number="1000600"
                                        ID="I08df9e62680811e8865b9f61650dcdcd">Rule 42(b)
                                </cite.query> provides that in furtherance of convenience or to avoid prejudice, the
                                court may in actions which it has consolidated, order the separate trial of any claim,
                                cross-claim, counterclaim, third-party claim, et cetera.
                                <eos/>
                                <bos/>
                                <end.quote refid="QT_0007"/>
                            </paratext>
                        </para>
                        <para>
                            <paratext><begin.quote ID="QT_0008"/>The provision in the proposed <cite.query
                                    w-src-number="0304913945" w-seq-number="00013" w-ref-type="LQ"
                                    w-normalized-cite="28USCAS1407" w-pub-number="1000546"
                                    ID="I08e89f10680811e8865b9f61650dcdcd">Section 1407
                            </cite.query> splitting off claims and sending them back to the originating district is
                                based on the analogy to <cite.query w-src-number="0304913945" w-seq-number="00014"
                                                                    w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="USFRCPR42"
                                                                    w-pub-number="1000600"
                                                                    ID="I08e89f11680811e8865b9f61650dcdcd">Rule 42(b)
                                </cite.query> and I think that is correct.
                                <eos/>
                                <bos/>
                                <end.quote refid="QT_0008"/>
                            </paratext>
                        </para>
                        <para>
                            <paratext><begin.quote ID="QT_0009"/>Now, the other suggestion, as I understood it, was that
                                instead of transferring the case in toto for consolidated or coordinated pre-trial
                                proceedings, only certain questions might be transferred to the transferee court and
                                other issues left to be disposed of, presumably during the same period of time, by the
                                transferor court.
                                <eos/>
                                <bos/>It seems to me that there are at least three rather serious objections to that.
                                <eos/>
                                <bos/>
                                <end.quote refid="QT_0009"/>
                            </paratext>
                        </para>
                        <para>
                            <paratext><begin.quote ID="QT_0010"/>In the first place, I think it would be very difficult
                                to frame any satisfactory definition that would tell you what kinds of issues should be
                                dealt with by the transferee court and what kind by the transferor court, and I can
                                imagine a great deal of argument and discussion going on as to whether a particular
                                issue is of the kind that should be disposed of back home or should be disposed of by
                                the transferee court.
                                <eos/>
                                <bos/>
                                <end.quote refid="QT_0010"/>
                            </paratext>
                        </para>
                        <para>
                            <paratext><begin.quote ID="QT_0011"/>In the second place, it seems to me that it would be
                                exceedingly awkward to have the determination of issues in the case being made partly in
                                one jurisdiction and partly in another.
                                <eos/>
                                <bos/>
                                <end.quote refid="QT_0011"/>
                            </paratext>
                        </para>
                        <para>
                            <paratext><begin.quote ID="QT_0012"/>The idea that a case could be pending in two different
                                districts at the same time seems to be a most awkward and inconvenient idea, and there
                                are great problems of tithing that would be involved, I would suppose.
                                <eos/>
                                <bos/>Certainly it would be convenient to dispose of certain issues before you got on to
                                other issues if you had to decide that certain of these issues must first be determined
                                by another district court, the whole process of getting on with the co-ordinated or
                                common proceedings might be interrupted.
                                <eos/>
                                <bos/>
                                <end.quote refid="QT_0012"/>
                            </paratext>
                        </para>
                        <para>
                            <paratext><begin.quote ID="QT_0013"/>In the third place, it seems to me that the idea of
                                leaving anything pending in the transferor district while the consolidated proceedings
                                are going forward is really a way of depriving the judicial system of some of the
                                important advantages of bringing the cases together.
                                <eos/>
                                <bos/>
                                <end.quote refid="QT_0013"/>
                            </paratext>
                        </para>
                        <para>
                            <paratext><begin.quote ID="QT_0014"/>I think, for example, about the various rulings on
                                questions of law which came up early in the electrical equipment cases such as the
                                tolling of the statute of limitations, the effect of the fraudulent concealment
                                doctrine, the effect of the pleas of nolo contendere and so on.
                                <eos/>
                                <bos/>
                                <end.quote refid="QT_0014"/>
                            </paratext>
                        </para>
                        <para>
                            <paratext><begin.quote ID="QT_0015"/>I think one of the important things about the conduct
                                of the electrical equipment cases was that these questions were all brought on early for
                                hearing and were determined, appeals were taken and we did not have the <?pagebreak label="13"?>questions
                                decided at widely different times in the different parts of the litigation.
                                <eos/>
                                <bos/>
                                <end.quote refid="QT_0015"/>
                            </paratext>
                        </para>
                        <para>
                            <paratext><begin.quote ID="QT_0016"/>Also, there would certainly be an advantage in having
                                only one court decide those questions instead of having to get dozens of different
                                decisions in different courts with conflicts eventually resolved by appeal.
                                <eos/>
                                <bos/>
                                <end.quote refid="QT_0016"/>
                            </paratext>
                        </para>
                        <para>
                            <paratext><begin.quote ID="QT_0017"/>It seems to me, in short, that the suggestion of
                                leaving the litigation in this divided state is quite impractical and that the only way,
                                if one wants to leave a case determined partly in the originating district and partly in
                                the transferee district, to do it is the division in time that 3815 calls for, that is
                                to say, the case is moved for all purposes to the transferee district, up to the
                                conclusion of pre-trial proceedings, and then may be sent back.
                                <eos/>
                                <bos/>
                                <end.quote refid="QT_0017"/>[<footnote.reference
                                        refid="I01d809d0680911e88f4a9c1f64101294">7</footnote.reference>]
                            </paratext>
                        </para>
                    </display.quote>
                    <eos/>
                    <eop/>
                </para>
                <para>
                    <bop/>
                    <bos/>
                    <paratext>The Panel has clearly followed the judgment of Congress and has recognized the broad power
                        of the transferee court to decide all matters until remand occurs.[
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>
                        <footnote.reference refid="I01d809d1680911e88f4a9c1f64101294">8</footnote.reference>] The Panel
                        has regularly refused to transfer portions of single claims for coordinated or consolidated
                        pretrial proceedings while remanding other portions of the claims.[
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>
                        <footnote.reference refid="I01d830e0680911e88f4a9c1f64101294">9</footnote.reference>] That
                        piecemeal transfer would result in parallel proceedings in multiple courts, a result obviously
                        not intended by Congress.
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>In one decision the Panel rejected an attempt to transfer only discovery proceedings
                        relating to liability, leaving all damage questions in the transferor court.
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>The Panel stated:
                    </paratext>
                    <display.quote>
                        <para>
                            <paratext><begin.quote ID="QT_0018"/>We will not so restrict the transferee judge for we
                                think it more conducive to effective judicial management to allow him to determine which
                                issues are appropriate for coordinated or Consolidated pretrial proceedings and which
                                should be reserved for further proceedings following remand.
                                <eos/>
                                <bos/>
                                <end.quote refid="QT_0018"/>[<footnote.reference
                                        refid="I01d857f1680911e88f4a9c1f64101294">10</footnote.reference>]
                            </paratext>
                        </para>
                    </display.quote>
                    <paratext>The Supreme Court in <cite.query w-src-number="0304913945" w-serial-number="1998061318"
                                                               w-seq-number="00018" w-ref-type="RS"
                                                               w-pub-number="0000708"
                                                               ID="I08fb3cb2680811e8865b9f61650dcdcd">Lexecon
                    </cite.query> also relied on the legislative history of <cite.query w-src-number="0304913945"
                                                                                        w-seq-number="00019"
                                                                                        w-ref-type="LQ"
                                                                                        w-normalized-cite="28USCAS1407"
                                                                                        w-pub-number="1000546"
                                                                                        ID="I08fb3cb4680811e8865b9f61650dcdcd">
                        section 1407
                    </cite.query> in determining whether the statute authorized transferee judges to transfer cases to
                        themselves.[
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>
                        <footnote.reference refid="I01da53c0680911e88f4a9c1f64101294">11</footnote.reference>]
                    </paratext>
                    <eos/>
                    <eop/>
                </para>
                <para>
                    <bop/>
                    <bos/>
                    <paratext>Congress anticipated the natural limitations on transfer.
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>Without imposing any specific limitations in the statute, Congress recognized that
                        transfer would be inappropriate in certain circumstances.[
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>
                        <footnote.reference refid="I01da53c1680911e88f4a9c1f64101294">12</footnote.reference>] The
                        legislative history reflects Congress&apos;s recognition that establishing a single, fixed
                        standard for the transfer decision would be difficult and that a flexible standard is required.
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>The Panel has apparently followed the intention of the drafters, readily transferring
                        cases where many individual actions are involved and applying a more stringent standard <?pagebreak label="14"?> where
                        few cases would be affected (and benefitted) by transfer.[
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>
                        <footnote.reference refid="I01da7ad0680911e88f4a9c1f64101294">13</footnote.reference>]
                    </paratext>
                    <eos/>
                    <eop/>
                </para>
            </section.body>
        </section>
